{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1a693504-8769-40b1-bbc4-96eb6659e444","content":"I can help guide you on analyzing your .NET crash dump. Here's how:\n\n**Using `dotnet-dump analyze`** (cross-platform):\n```bash\n# Install if needed\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\n\n# Launch interactive analysis\ndotnet-dump analyze your-file.dmp\n```\n\nUseful commands inside the analyzer:\n| Command | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `clrstack` | Managed call stack of current thread |\n| `clrthreads` | List all managed threads |\n| `pe` (PrintException) | Show last exception details |\n| `dumpheap -stat` | Heap summary (memory issues) |\n| `setthread <id>` + `clrstack` | Inspect other threads |\n\n**Typical workflow to find crash root cause:**\n1. Run `pe` to check for an unhandled exception\n2. Run `clrthreads` to find threads with exceptions\n3. Run `setthread <id>` then `clrstack` on suspicious threads\n4. Use `dumpobj <addr>` to inspect exception/object details\n\n**Alternatives:**\n- **Visual Studio** (Windows) — open the `.dmp` directly, click \"Debug with Managed Only\"\n- **lldb + SOS** (Linux/macOS) — `lldb --core your-file.dmp` then load the SOS plugin\n\nWould you like me to walk you through any of these steps in more detail?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b4ba4f9f-6441-4f81-858e-8bc063b500a7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about analyzing a .dmp crash dump file. Let me check the available skills - there's a `dump-collect` skill, but its description says it's for \"Configure and collect crash dumps\" and explicitly states \"DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze, profiling or tracing.\"\n\nSo the dump-collect skill is not appropriate here. I should help the user directly with guidance on analyzing their dump file.","outputTokens":466,"requestId":"6405:16C6BF:5FFC633:6BA6D7E:69EC1B41"},"id":"aa384060-8c97-4781-a678-46188f012464","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:39:2